WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.520
 So now we're going to start producing the actual output

00:00:02.520 --> 00:00:05.800
 of our application in the views and using templates.

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:07.760
 And there's a lot to cover here.

00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:10.320
 So up till now, we've been starting

00:00:10.320 --> 00:00:12.160
 to talk about URLs, which are simple.

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:15.720
 It says when you get the request with a URL of this format,

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:18.520
 choose a view and send it to that view.

00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:21.400
 We're going to talk a lot about views dot py and templates

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:22.920
 in an upcoming lecture.

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:24.320
 We'll talk about forms.

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:26.960
 And we spent a bunch of time talking about models dot py

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:29.600
 and how the models can talk to Python code,

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:31.480
 talk to the shell, how the models get

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:33.560
 in for how we write to the database

00:00:33.560 --> 00:00:35.480
 and how we read from the database.

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:37.600
 So we're starting to fill parts in.

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:39.240
 As we put the views together, we're

00:00:39.240 --> 00:00:42.760
 really starting to really create our entire application.

00:00:42.760 --> 00:00:45.160
 And I know it's taken a while to get to the point

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:50.280
 where we can get to the point where we see the whole thing.

00:00:50.280 --> 00:00:53.800
 So I just want to say that from time to time, wherever you

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:56.520
 have dj-free samples, whether it's on your laptop

00:00:56.520 --> 00:01:00.920
 or whether it's on Python anywhere,

00:01:00.920 --> 00:01:03.600
 you should do a get pull from time to time

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:05.580
 because I'm always working on these samples.

00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:07.120
 And I want you to make sure you have

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:09.160
 the latest copies of these samples.

00:01:09.160 --> 00:01:10.520
 Sometimes I add little bits.

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:13.440
 I don't change the samples, but I add bits of documentation

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:16.080
 as I'm like, oh, I should have added that.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:19.000
 So views are like the core of the application.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.840
 I mean, the URLs find their way to views.

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:25.600
 Models tend to serve the needs of views,

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:28.800
 act as this layer to allow views to write and read

00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:30.140
 the database.

00:01:30.140 --> 00:01:34.840
 And so the views.py has a model aspect

00:01:34.840 --> 00:01:36.400
 and it handles incoming data.

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:38.720
 When we get the forms and post data,

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:41.000
 then we copy that into the database.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.320
 The views.py decides sometimes whether or not

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:47.200
 to send the user to a different screen

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:51.040
 or if it's going to produce the actual screen in the HTML,

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:53.640
 it produces that HTML, often using template,

00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:55.000
 and then sends it back.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:58.280
 So the views are where the work really gets done.

00:01:58.280 --> 00:02:01.960
 And what you see is you write a lot of code in the views.

00:02:01.960 --> 00:02:05.600
 You write one line in the URL, few lines in the models file,

00:02:05.600 --> 00:02:08.000
 and then lots of stuff in the views.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.480
 And I consider the templates kind of part of the views

00:02:10.480 --> 00:02:11.960
 as well.

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:13.900
 So the first thing that Django does

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:16.600
 when it receives an incoming document, a request

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:19.920
 for a document, it basically parses that URL.

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:23.000
 And the first thing after the domain name

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:25.600
 is generally the application.

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:28.600
 So remember that Django has a project.

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:30.080
 And then underneath that, there's

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:31.320
 one or more applications.

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:35.120
 And each of the DJ4E samples, you see lots of applications.

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:37.880
 Each application kind of to show a little bit of sample

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:39.480
 code for a topic.

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:43.480
 And so that second part of the URL,

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:46.320
 that is the application name.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:47.800
 And for all intents and purposes,

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:51.280
 it's also the folder name within the Django project.

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:55.360
 Now within that, usually the next chunk is the view.

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:58.320
 And so that view within application,

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:05.800
 the view within application is defined in urls.py.

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:08.800
 And then after that, there are two kinds of parameters.

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:10.360
 One is like a key value parameter

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:12.320
 that comes after a question mark.

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:14.160
 It also uses ampersands for that.

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:17.240
 And then sometimes we just put after slashes.

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:22.720
 This is more of a REST style URL that's very pretty.

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:24.560
 And you put the parameters right on the URL

00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:26.280
 rather than the question mark, which

00:03:26.280 --> 00:03:29.680
 is sort of the old school for doing all this stuff.

00:03:29.680 --> 00:03:33.680
 So there is this thing in Django called the URL dispatcher.

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:36.000
 I sort of call it router on my picture.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.040
 It's basically to get you to be able to define the URLs

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:42.040
 and how those URLs are to be parsed and handled

00:03:42.040 --> 00:03:46.600
 and how those URLs to be routed to the various bits of view

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:47.520
 code.

00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:50.200
 And so we do this in urls.py.

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:52.800
 There are three basic patterns.

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:56.200
 First, you might route a particular URL pattern

00:03:56.200 --> 00:03:58.200
 to a predefined class.

00:03:58.200 --> 00:04:00.880
 And you'll see the example of that coming up.

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.400
 Or there's sort of functions, really old school function,

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:08.600
 that take this request, which is an object that

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:12.360
 captures all of the data, the parameters, the URL,

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:15.360
 whether it was a secure request or not, what host it came from,

00:04:15.360 --> 00:04:17.320
 what's the IP address it came from.

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:20.480
 All that stuff is wrapped up into this request object, which

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:22.120
 we'll talk about in a second.

00:04:22.120 --> 00:04:24.520
 And that view function looks at that request object,

00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:28.000
 decides what to do, talks to the database maybe,

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.600
 and then sends back a response, whether it's

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:33.480
 a redirect or some HTML.

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:35.440
 And the function is kind of the low level thing.

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:37.600
 But you can also then define a class.

00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:42.640
 And defining classes, as we'll see, is really quite nice.

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:45.960
 The classes have methods, like for get and for post,

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:49.320
 depending on the kind of incoming HTTP request

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:50.160
 that we're handling.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:53.760
 And it also, in those methods, the request

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:57.840
 and any other URL parameters can also be sent in.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:01.760
 So let's take a look at a sample urls.py from views.

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:06.720
 And we see examples of all three kinds of these routes.

00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:08.800
 URL patterns is a global variable.

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:10.720
 It's just a list.

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:12.520
 But it has very special meaning.

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:15.760
 This list has very special meaning to Django.

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:19.000
 And you see these path commands.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.200
 And there's other ways to describe these things.

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:22.440
 And then you have the path.

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:25.560
 And the blank path means sort of just slash right

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:28.040
 after the application name.

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:30.760
 And then we have which view to send it to.

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:34.320
 And so this template view as view,

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:37.560
 this is basically to save you from writing code

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:40.520
 if all you want to do is take a template out of the templates

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:42.760
 folder and return it.

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:45.160
 So you don't have to write your own code in views.py.

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:47.000
 And so it's already there.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.960
 And that's why we go into Django views generic import template

00:05:49.960 --> 00:05:50.560
 view.

00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:53.560
 And we're going to say, you know what, I'm going to route--

00:05:53.560 --> 00:05:56.040
 I mean, I wrote that template.

00:05:56.040 --> 00:05:58.920
 But I just don't want to write the code to go send that.

00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:00.720
 We just read that template and send it back.

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:05.440
 And so this is a predefined bit of Django that does this for us.

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:07.280
 Sort of the more old school thing

00:06:07.280 --> 00:06:09.800
 is this syntax right here.

00:06:09.800 --> 00:06:16.320
 And basically from.import views pulls in views slash views.py.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:20.040
 And then this, you will see our functions inside there.

00:06:20.040 --> 00:06:24.000
 And then these are classes also from our views.py

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.920
 for this particular application.

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:28.840
 And the syntax is a little weird.

00:06:28.840 --> 00:06:30.440
 This is the module we imported.

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:31.680
 This is a class from that.

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:34.880
 And then as view is a static method

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:37.640
 that returns a function that then can

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:40.760
 respond to the incoming requests.

00:06:40.760 --> 00:06:44.200
 And we'll see these as we kind of go through these.

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:46.800
 So up next, we're going to actually look at the views.py

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:50.160
 and take a look at the views.

